Linear Independence
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The matrices
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{gathered}A=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
2 & -4\\
3 & -6
\end{array}\right],\ B=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
4 & 2 & 6\\
-1 & -9 & 7
\end{array}\right],\ C=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
3 & 3 & -5\\
-8 & 2 & 0\\
5 & -4 & 7
\end{array}\right],\\
D=\left[\begin{array}{cccccc}
-11 & 10 & -5 & 3 & 7 & -1\\
-8 & -1 & 6 & 6 & 0 & 1\\
-2 & 8 & 7 & -9 & -15 & -3\\
8 & 5 & -10 & -7 & 5 & 2
\end{array}\right]
\end{gathered}
\]

\end_inset

have something in common.
 Each matrix has a column that can be written as a linear combination of
 the other columns in the matrix.
 Not all matrices have this property, and there is an important distinction
 between those that do and those that do not.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Compare 
\begin_inset Formula $E=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
2 & -8\\
1 & 5
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, for example.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, neither column is a multiple of the other so neither column can be written
 as a linear combination of the other.
 However, the second column of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $-2$
\end_inset

 times the first:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $A_{:,2}=-2A_{:,1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You may be struggling a little bit to see this as a linear combination,
 but nothing in the definition of linear combination requires more than
 one term.
 So if an object is a multiple of another it is a linear combination of
 it.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that 
\begin_inset Formula $\det A=0$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\det E\neq0$
\end_inset

.
 The matrix with one column that can be written as a linear combination
 of the others has 0 determinant while the matrix whose columns can not
 be written as linear combinations of the others has nonzero determinant.
 We made a similar observation about linear combinations of the rows of
 a matrix and its determinant in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec:The-Determinant"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $B,C,D$
\end_inset

 it is less clear that one column is a linear combination of the others,
 but you can check that
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $B_{:,3}=2B_{:,1}-B_{:,2}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $C_{:,1}=-4C_{:,2}+3C_{:,3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
\begin_inset Formula $D_{:,5}=2D_{:,1}+2D_{:,2}+0D_{:,3}+3D_{:,4}+0D_{:,6}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Don't be misled by the suggestion that 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

one column
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is a linear combination of the others, however.
 It is true, but does not tell the whole story.
 In no case is the column written in terms of the others special.
 For matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, for example, we could have easily pointed out that the first column is
 
\begin_inset Formula $-\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 the second.
 The first column is a linear combination of the second, and the second
 column is a linear combination of the first.
 Neither one should take priority.
\end_layout

