\begin_layout Standard
The fact that columns within the matrix can be written as linear combinations
 of the others is captured, but no particular column is prominent, motivating
 the following definition.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be a set of objects on which addition and scalar mutliplication are defined
 and which contains an additive identity, called 0.
 For scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2},\ldots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 and objects 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1},b_{2},\ldots,b_{n}$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1},b_{2},\ldots,b_{n}$
\end_inset

 are 
\series bold
linearly independent
\series default
 or that 
\begin_inset Formula $\{b_{1},b_{2},\ldots,b_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is a linearly independent set if the only solution of 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{1}b_{1}+x_{2}b_{2}+\cdots+x_{n}b_{n}=0\label{eq:linear-independence-definition}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

is the trivial solution 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=x_{2}=\cdots=x_{n}=0$
\end_inset

.
 Otherwise the objects 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1},b_{2},\ldots,b_{n}$
\end_inset

 are 
\series bold
linearly dependent
\series default
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\{b_{1},b_{2},\ldots,b_{n}\}$
\end_inset

 is a linearly dependent set.
 Note that the 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 in (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:linear-independence-definition"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) is the object 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

, not necessarily the number 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition to being a statement about the set of objects rather than one
 special member of the set, this definition handles the case when one of
 the objects in the set is the 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 object (additive identity) itself.
 In this case, that particular object is special.
 It can be written as a linear combination of the others (with all coefficients
 equal to zero) but it is not necessarily the case that any of the other
 objects can be written as a linear combination of the remaining ones.
 As a simple example, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E=\left[\begin{array}{ccc}
1 & -4 & 0\\
2 & 5 & 0\\
3 & -1 & 0
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

The third column is a zero vector.
 Accordingly,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E_{:,3}=0E_{:,1}+0E_{:,2}
\]

\end_inset

so the third column is a linear combination of the first two.
 However, neither of the first two columns is a linear combination of the
 others.
 This is clear since the first two columns are not multiples of one another.
 In the context of the definition, we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
0E_{:,1}+0E_{:,2}+E_{:,3}=0,
\]

\end_inset

a nontrivial linear combination of the columns that sums to 0.
 No fanfare.
 No notes of special cases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Free variables, solution sets of linear systems, and pivot positions of
 matrices are all directly connected to the concept of linear independence.
 
\end_layout

