\backslash
begin{digression}{Proof by Contraposition}
\end_layout

\end_inset

Suppose you are trying to prove that if some statement, call it 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, is true, then some other statement, call it 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is true.
 In short, you are trying to prove that if 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is true then 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is true.
 Then it is just as good to prove the contrapositive claim, if 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is false then 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is false, because if the contrapositive is true then it is impossible to
 have both 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 false and 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 true.
 In other words, if 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is true so is 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 cannot be false at the same time 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is true (and that means if 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is true then 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is true).
 By similar logic, if any statement in a list of equivalent statements is
 false, they are all false.
